<div class='communityQuestion'>
<div class='questionText'>
<a href="/questions/1627985-anyone-know-where-the-following-quote-in">Anyone know where the following quote in the book comes from? 
&quot;Whoso has den well schal go to blysse. Whoso has don evil to peyne I-wysse&quot;</a>
</div>
<div class='communityQAFooter questionFooter'>
<ul class='questionFooterActions'>
<li class='footerItem like'>
<span class='likeItContainer' id='like_container_community_question_1627985'><a rel="nofollow" class="jsLike like_it" href="https://www.goodreads.com/user/new?remember=true&amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Fshow%2F60707.A_Month_in_the_Country">like</a></span>

</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionTimestamp'>
<a href="/questions/1627985-anyone-know-where-the-following-quote-in">2 years ago</a>
</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionPermalink'>
<a href="/questions/1627985-anyone-know-where-the-following-quote-in">See all 4 answers</a>
</li>
</ul>
</div>

</div>
<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/20604870-caryatid"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1602608544i/20604870._UX100_CR0,41,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/20604870-caryatid">Caryatid</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">As a medievalist, I felt I had to answer this question! <br/> All the Middle English quotes in A Month in the Country come from John Mirk’s Instructions fo<a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">As a medievalist, I felt I had to answer this question! <br /> All the Middle English quotes in A Month in the Country come from John Mirk’s Instructions for Parish Priests. Mirk was a canon regular at Lilleshall Priory in Shropshire. (A "canon regular" is a kind of monk. They had to follow a "rule" (Latin "regula"), that is, the modes of life mandated by their monastic order.)<br /> Mirk wrote the Instructions in the early 15th century. <a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
</div>
