<div id="review_2339403234" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2339403234" />
    <a title="Tras" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/17620211-tras"><img alt="Tras" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1553624744p2/17620211.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2339403234?book_show_action=true">Mar 26, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tras" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tras" href="/user/show/17620211-tras">Tras</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17620211-tras?shelf=favourites">favourites</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2339403234" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8799634195889764167"><i>We can ask and ask but we can’t have again what once seemed ours for ever – the way things looked, that church alone in the fields, a bed on a belfry floor, a remembered voice, the touch of a hand, a loved face. They’ve gone and you can only wait for the pain to pass.</i><br/><br/>An England that no longer exists - the dying embers of the horse age, Europe devastated by the First World War, and the annihilation of several generations of men.<br/><br/>In a small Yorkshire church, a medieval mural has been discovered und</span>
  <span id="freeText8799634195889764167" style="display:none"><i>We can ask and ask but we can’t have again what once seemed ours for ever – the way things looked, that church alone in the fields, a bed on a belfry floor, a remembered voice, the touch of a hand, a loved face. They’ve gone and you can only wait for the pain to pass.</i><br /><br />An England that no longer exists - the dying embers of the horse age, Europe devastated by the First World War, and the annihilation of several generations of men.<br /><br />In a small Yorkshire church, a medieval mural has been discovered under layers of dirt and whitewash. Tim Birkin is a WW1 veteran, and one of the few men in the country with the necessary skills to uncover the mural. He is hired to do so by a less than friendly vicar. His experiences in the war left their mark - physically and mentally (how could they not?) - but he has been told that time is the only thing that will help to mend both the visible and invisible wounds. A number of weeks in the countryside seem like a perfect solution.<br /><br />'A Month in the Country' is an exquisitely poignant story set in the wonderfully hot summer of 1920. Essentially, this is one man's rediscovery of the innumerable simple pleasures that the very act of just 'living' can impart, as he comes to terms with the transient nature of happiness. Life often introduces us to brief yet perfect moments - fleeting moments of beauty, solace, and attraction. Such things can leave a lasting impression upon our very being, but are often gone in the blink of an eye - never to reappear in that exact same form. Lingering only in threads of memory.<br /><br />Completing the book left me with an unforgettable melancholy. It is beautifully written with a cast of supporting characters that will make you long to be a part of the village. It has already made itself comfy on the couch of my memory.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8799634195889764167" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


