    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_223754326" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/223754326" />
    <a title="Declan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5848260-declan"><img alt="Declan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1427664982p2/5848260.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/223754326?book_show_action=true">Oct 15, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Declan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Declan" href="/user/show/5848260-declan">Declan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5848260-declan?shelf=nyrb">nyrb</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer223754326" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9130328573656742559">The descriptions in &apos;A Month in the Country&apos; do not draw particular attention to ambient sounds or noise (it is in any case a consistently subtle book in which everything occurs with a minimum of fuss), but I suspect that one of the major comforts of Tom Birkin&apos;s time in Oxgodby, and one of the reasons he is content for the work of restoration to take longer than he had intended, is that the rich, enveloping quite of the church - birdsong outside; the rhythmic tapping of his tools; the barely di</span>
  <span id="freeText9130328573656742559" style="display:none">The descriptions in 'A Month in the Country' do not draw particular attention to ambient sounds or noise (it is in any case a consistently subtle book in which everything occurs with a minimum of fuss), but I suspect that one of the major comforts of Tom Birkin's time in Oxgodby, and one of the reasons he is content for the work of restoration to take longer than he had intended, is that the rich, enveloping quite of the church - birdsong outside; the rhythmic tapping of his tools; the barely discernible sound of Moon digging - is a startling contrast to the uproar of war which assailed his ears so recently.<br /><br />That work of restoration is, of course, personal as well as practical. He is slowly removing the accretions of many decades from the wall at the back of a small church, to reveal an exceptional work of medieval painting. But - and again there is nothing laboured about the way this is done - he also begins to reveal and reconcile aspects of himself that have been sundered by the war and a difficult marriage. The purposeful nature of his work and the excitement of what he, day-by-day, is discovering about the mural together with the comradeship of archaeologist Moon and his easily formed friendships with several of the people in the village help him begin to understand the importance of human contact and community involvement. More than with any other, his conversations with the vicars beautiful wife give him a real sense of what it is to hope again; to feel the absolute nowness of this particular time; to comprehend the persistence of desire despite all that he has experienced. It brings him too, through two visits to the vicarage, to an understanding of the undeclared despair that can also dwell in this environment. <br /><br />All of what he relates in the book is told from the perspective of many years hence and so there is a sense that the entire story has gained a dusty layer of nostalgia and how could it not? It was a lovely month, spent in a beautiful, remote place, among gracious and complex people. It was, above all, a time that allowed for repair and, most unexpectedly, a time replete with possibility, even if little of it was realised back then. This, I'd like to suggest, might be its soundtrack: <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EkQbzZgwfl0">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EkQbz...</a> .</span>
  <a data-text-id="9130328573656742559" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


